ll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Conteville, Calvados, Normandie, Francie"},"da":{"about 1020–28 January 1069":"omkring 1020–28. januar 1069","1020–1069":"1020–1069","1026–1053":"1026–1053","1026–Female":"1026–Afdød","1060–1136":"1060–1136","1053–1135":"1053–1135","0991–1021":"0991–1021","about 1060":"omkring 1060","1021":"1021","1053":"1053","1020":"1020","1068–28 January 1069":"fra 1068 til 28. januar 1069","1060":"1060","28 January 1069":"28. januar 1069","circa 1021":"omkring 1021","1136":"1136","1026":"1026","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","0991":"0991","about 1020":"omkring 1020","about 1053":"omkring 1053","Altyre, Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Skotland, United Kingdom","Durham, Northumberland, England":"Carham, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Skotland, United Kingdom","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Skotland","Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Conteville, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"about 1020–28 January 1069":"circa 1020–28 januari 1069","1020–1069":"1020–1069","1026–1053":"1026–1053","1026–Female":"1026–Overleden","1060–1136":"1060–1136","1053–1135":"1053–1135","0991–1021":"0991–1021","about 1060":"circa 1060","1021":"1021","1053":"1053","1020":"1020","1068–28 January 1069":"van 1068 to 28 januari 1069","1060":"1060","28 January 1069":"28 januari 1069","circa 1021":"circa 1021","1136":"1136","1026":"1026","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","0991":"0991","about 1020":"circa 1020","about 1053":"circa 1053","Altyre, Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Durham, Northumberland, England":"Carham, Northumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Schotland","Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Conteville, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"about 1020–28 January 1069":"about 1020–28 January 1069","1020–1069":"1020–1069","1026–1053":"1026–1053","1026–Female":"1026–Deceased","1060–1136":"1060–1136","1053–1135":"1053–1135","0991–1021":"0991–1021","about 1060":"about 1060","1021":"1021","1053":"1053","1020":"1020","1068–28 January 1069":"from 1068 to 28 January 1069","1060":"1060","28 January 1069":"28 January 1069","circa 1021":"about 1021","1136":"1136","1026":"1026","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","0991":"0991","about 1020":"about 1020","about 1053":"about 1053","Altyre, Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Durham, Northumberland, England":"Carham, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Scotland, United Kingdom","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Comyn","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English, Irish:  see  Cumming  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cumming","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): most probably a habitational name from Bosc-Benard-Commin in Eure, France. This place lies on the edge of the Forêt de Rouvray, near Rouen, in the heart of the district from which came numerous Domesday barons, and so is much more likely to be the source of the name than Comines in Nord. The name is also possibly derived from the personal name <i>Cumin</i>, which is found in Norfolk, Lincolnshire, and Yorkshire in the 12th and 13th centuries and may be of Breton origin, according to Reaney. Compare Old Breton <i>Cunmin</i>, which also appears as <i>Cumin</i>, and is from <i>con-</i> ‘hound’ with an uncertain second element, perhaps the <i>min</i> ‘edge’ which is found in other personal names.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cuimín</b> (or <b>Ó Cuimín</b>) ‘son (or ‘descendant’) of <i>Cuimín</i>’, a personal name formed from a diminutive of <i>cam</i> ‘crooked’. There was a 7th-century abbot of Iona named <i>Cumin</i>. In Scotland, this Irish surname became confused with the Norman name.","History: A notable bearer of the Norman surname is Wilhelmus Comyn, Bishop of Durham, who came north to Scotland with King David I in 1124 and was appointed Chancellor of Scotland. He established his nephew Richard in Tynedale and Roxburghshire, and Richard also rose to be Chancellor of Scotland. The Comyn or Cumming family gained the earldoms of Buchan and Menteith and rose to be the most powerful noble family in Scotland in the century before the rise of King Robert Bruce."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert De Comyn Earl Of Northumberland was born about 1020, in Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France as the son of John De Tynedale, De Comyn. He had at least 1 son with Maud Cumton of Morayshire. He died on 28 January 1069, in Carham, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"about 1020–28 January 1069":"umbes 1020–28. jaanuar 1069","1020–1069":"1020–1069","1026–1053":"1026–1053","1026–Female":"1026–Surnud","1060–1136":"1060–1136","1053–1135":"1053–1135","0991–1021":"0991–1021","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1021":"1021","1053":"1053","1020":"1020","1068–28 January 1069":"1068 kuni 28. jaanuar 1069","1060":"1060","28 January 1069":"28. jaanuar 1069","circa 1021":"umbes 1021","1136":"1136","1026":"1026","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","0991":"0991","about 1020":"umbes 1020","about 1053":"umbes 1053","Altyre, Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Durham, Northumberland, England":"Carham, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Argyll, Scotland":"Argyll, Scotland","Conteville, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Conteville, Calvados, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1020–28 January 1069":"noin 1020–28. tammikuuta 1069","1020–1069":"1020–1069","1026–1053":"1026–1053","1026–Female":"1026–Kuollut","1060–1136":"1060–1136","1053–1135":"1053–1135","0991–1021":"0991–1021","about 1060":"noin 1060","1021":"1021","1053":"1053","1020":"1020","1068–28 January 1069":"vuodesta 1068 vuoteen 28. tammikuuta 1069","1060":"1060","28 January 1069":"28. tammikuuta 1069","circa 1021":"noin 1021","1136":"1136","1026":"1026","1135":"1135","1069":"1069","0991":"0991","about 1020":"noin 1020","about 1053":"noin 1053","Altyre, Morayshire, Scotland":"Moray, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningasku